    <!-- ABSTRACT -->
    <div class="section-page">
        <h1 style="page-break-before: avoid;">Abstract</h1>
        <p>Visually impaired individuals encounter physical safety hazards when navigating unknown or dynamic environments. Existing electronic travel aids rely heavily on cloud APIs, creating network latency (500ms - 2s) and reliability issues during signal drops. Additionally, most systems announce directions robotically on every frame, leading to cognitive fatigue.</p>
        <p>This handbook presents <strong>PathVision Final v1.0</strong>, an event-driven, local-first navigation assistant that operates entirely locally on laptop hardware (NVIDIA RTX 2050 4GB VRAM). The system integrates a TensorRT safe path segmentation model and a monocular depth estimation model (Depth Anything V2) to build a unified spatial description. The decisions are fed into a local Qwen LLM and synthesized using Kokoro TTS. To optimize hardware usage, we implemented background reasoning and logging workers, in-place NumPy normalization, and GPU-bound softmax decoding. The system runs at a stable <strong>42.3 FPS</strong>, offering immediate safety responses, conversational updates, and priority voice preemption to maximize safety and user experience.</p>
    </div>

