    <!-- CHAPTER 1 -->
    <h1>Chapter 1: Introduction</h1>
    <h2>1.1 Blind Navigation Challenges</h2>
    <p>Independent mobility is one of the greatest challenges faced by visually impaired individuals. Obstacles such as low-hanging branches, parked vehicles, indoor furniture, and sudden floor drop-offs present constant physical safety hazards. Traditional orientation tools, primarily white canes and guide dogs, provide immediate tactile feedback but have limited detection ranges and cannot anticipate hazards several meters ahead.</p>
    <h2>1.2 Limitations of Existing Electronic Travel Aids</h2>
    <p>Many recent computer vision solutions attempt to use cloud-based pipelines where images are sent to remote servers for processing. While this offloads heavy computation, it introduces severe round-trip network latencies ranging from 500 milliseconds to over 2 seconds. In active walking navigation, a delay of one second means the user travels up to 1.5 meters before a warning is received. This latency presents an unacceptable safety risk.</p>
    <h2>1.3 Motivation & Objectives</h2>
    <p>PathVision Final is designed as a local-first system that runs entirely on laptop hardware with an NVIDIA RTX 2050 GPU. It bypasses network requirements, ensuring reliability during offline scenarios. Crucially, the system moves away from robotic command-repetition by using a Situation Manager that detects context changes, values silence over chatter, and interacts like a calm companion.</p>

    <!-- CHAPTER 2 -->
    <h1>Chapter 2: Overall System Architecture</h1>
    <h2>2.1 Complete Architectural Flowchart</h2>
    <pre>
[Camera Ingest] (640x480)
      │
      ▼
[Frame Preprocessing] (Downscaled 320x240, Normalized, Transposed)
      │
      ├──────────────────────────────┐
      ▼                              ▼
[PathVision Segmenter]      [Depth Anything V2]
(Safe Walkable Area)        (Dense Relative Depth Map)
      │                              │
      ▼                              ▼
[GPU Softmax Decoder]       [In-place normalizer]
      │                              │
      └──────────────┬───────────────┘
                     ▼
             [Scene Fusion] (Walkable Proximity quantiles)
                     │
                     ▼
          [Path Geometry Analyzer] (Centroid offset calculation)
                     │
                     ▼
            [Safety Evaluator] (Danger, Caution, Safe state)
                     │
                     ▼
          [Steering Decision] (FORWARD, LEFT, RIGHT, SLOW, STOP)
                     │
                     ▼
          [Situation Manager] (Classify environmental context)
                     │
                     ▼
           [Qwen LLM (Ollama)] (Asynchronous guidance generation)
                     │
                     ▼
            [Kokoro Speaker] (Preemptive Priority Queue)
    </pre>
    <h2>2.2 Core Blocks and Connections</h2>
    <p>The system couples real-time visual perception with high-level conversational reasoning, ensuring safety decisions remain deterministic while guidance is natural and companion-like. By using local TensorRT deep learning engines and local Large Language Models (LLMs), the system acts like a supportive, talking companion.</p>

    <!-- CHAPTER 3 -->
    <h1>Chapter 3: Folder Structure</h1>
    <h2>3.1 Core Directory Layout</h2>
    <pre>
PathVision_Final/
├── main.py                     # Main execution runtime orchestrator
├── config.py                   # Centralized configuration structures
├── perception/
│   ├── pathvision_trt.py       # PathVision Segmentation TensorRT wrapper
│   ├── depth_trt.py           # Depth Anything V2 TensorRT wrapper
│   └── scene_fusion.py         # Multi-model spatial fusion engine
├── navigation/
│   ├── path_geometry.py       # Geometric analyzer for walkable paths
│   ├── safety.py               # Safety state evaluator
│   └── decision.py             # Direction command generator
├── reasoning/
│   ├── situation_manager.py    # Situation and Interaction mode classifier
│   ├── conversation_memory.py   # Speech deduplication and reassurance controller
│   ├── prompts.py              # LLM prompt builder and offline fallback logic
│   └── scene_memory.py         # Historical scene data ring buffer
└── speech/
    └── kokoro.py               # Preemptive priority Kokoro TTS speaker
    </pre>
    <h2>3.2 Folder Explanations</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>`perception/`:</strong> Manages the TensorRT engines for PathVision and Depth Anything V2.</li>
        <li><strong>`navigation/`:</strong> Processes binary segmentations to extract centers, widths, and safety commands.</li>
        <li><strong>`reasoning/`:</strong> Classifies user situations and constructs prompts for the LLM.</li>
        <li><strong>`speech/`:</strong> Coordinates Kokoro TTS playback with a priority queue.</li>
        <li><strong>`learning/`:</strong> Writes JSONL logs and captures dataset frames asynchronously.</li>
    </ul>

    <!-- CHAPTER 4 -->
    <h1>Chapter 4: Project Pipeline</h1>
    <h2>4.1 Frame Processing Pipeline</h2>
    <p>The processing pipeline runs sequentially to transform camera inputs into guidance. The stages are described below:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Stage 1: Camera Acquisition:</strong> Webcam frames are acquired at `640x480` resolution using a non-blocking background thread (`AsyncCamera`) to avoid camera capture latency blocking the main loop.</li>
        <li><strong>Stage 2: PathVision TensorRT Segmentation:</strong> The frame is resized to `320x240`, normalized, and passed to the PathVision TRT engine. The engine outputs pixel-level logits classifying regions as walkable safe path or obstacles.</li>
        <li><strong>Stage 3: Depth Anything V2 Estimation:</strong> The frame is processed through the Depth Anything TRT engine at `518x518` resolution, outputting a dense depth map measuring relative distance.</li>
        <li><strong>Stage 4: Spatial Sensor Fusion:</strong> The depth map is resized to `320x240` to align with the safe walkable mask. Proximity stats are extracted within the walkable boundaries to calculate the nearest obstacle distance.</li>
        <li><strong>Stage 5: Navigation and Steering Decision:</strong> The path center index, Safe Area Ratio, and walkable bottom width are calculated. The safety evaluator checks obstacle clearance and commands a command (FORWARD, LEFT, RIGHT, SLOW, STOP).</li>
        <li><strong>Stage 6: Situation Classification:</strong> The situation manager evaluates transitions and maps them to an Interaction Mode (Orientation, Guidance, Alert, Description).</li>
        <li><strong>Stage 7: Speech Synthesis:</strong> If allowed by the conversation memory, the text is enqueued in the preemptive speech queue and spoken via Kokoro TTS.</li>
    </ul>

    <!-- CHAPTER 5 -->
    <h1>Chapter 5: Camera System</h1>
    <h2>5.1 Camera Data Ingest</h2>
    <p>A dedicated background thread (AsyncCamera) captures frames from the webcam at 640x480 resolution. This isolates camera grab time from model execution.</p>
    <h2>5.2 Image Preprocessing & Scaling</h2>
    <p>Raw camera frames of size 640x480 are downscaled to 320x240 pixels to match the input dimensions of the PathVision model. This downscaling reduces the pixel volume by 4x, saving GPU compute cycles. The image is normalized and transposed to a (1, 3, 240, 320) shape.</p>

    <!-- CHAPTER 6 -->
    <h1>Chapter 6: PathVision TensorRT</h1>
    <h2>6.1 Safe Walkable Area Segmentation</h2>
    <p>PathVision is a semantic segmentation model trained to identify walkable floor areas. The model categorizes pixels into three classes: Unsafe/Obstacle, Safe Walkable Path, and Path Boundaries. The ONNX model was compiled into an optimized TensorRT engine with FP16 precision, reducing inference latency on the local RTX 2050 GPU.</p>
    <h2>6.2 GPU Decoder & Post-Processing</h2>
    <p>To avoid the latency of copying raw float logits to the CPU, we run the softmax and argmax calculations directly on the GPU using PyTorch CUDA operations. The binary mask is then cleaned using morphological operations (dilation and erosion) to remove noise, producing the final `safe_mask` used by the Scene Fusion engine.</p>

    <!-- CHAPTER 7 -->
    <h1>Chapter 7: Depth Anything TensorRT</h1>
    <h2>7.1 Monocular Depth Estimation</h2>
    <p>The Depth Anything V2 engine estimates relative depth across the entire frame. The engine outputs a (518, 518) depth map, where values are normalized to a 0.0 (near) to 1.0 (far) scale. This relative depth map provides the distance information needed to identify obstacles.</p>
    <h2>7.2 Complementing PathVision</h2>
    <p>While PathVision identifies walkable floor coordinates, it does not measure distance or detect obstacles above floor level (e.g., low branches or hanging signs). The depth estimator complements PathVision by measuring distance to nearby hazards, allowing the system to identify objects blocking the path of travel.</p>

    <!-- CHAPTER 8 -->
    <h1>Chapter 8: Scene Fusion</h1>
    <h2>8.1 Sensor Fusion Logic</h2>
    <p>Scene Fusion aligns the safe walkable path mask with the monocular depth map to isolate obstacles blocking the user's path. By combining these inputs, the system calculates distance metrics only within the walkable path, minimizing false alarms from walls or objects outside the path of travel.</p>
    <h2>8.2 Data Contract Fields</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>`depth.nearest_obstacle_distance`: The 10th percentile of depth values within the walkable path, representing the closest obstacle.</li>
        <li>`path_geometry.bottom_width_ratio`: Walkable path width directly in front of the user's feet, used to identify narrowing corridors.</li>
        <li>`safety.state`: The safety state (SAFE, CAUTION, DANGER) resolved by the Safety Evaluator.</li>
    </ul>

    <!-- CHAPTER 9 -->
    <h1>Chapter 9: Situation Manager</h1>
    <h2>9.1 Situation Classification</h2>
    <p>The SituationManager class maps scene geometry, depth statistics, and historical transitions to a specific environmental context. By identifying transitions (e.g., crossing a doorway or moving into a new room), the system updates the conversational mode to keep the user informed.</p>
    <h2>9.2 Conversational Modes</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Orientation Mode:</strong> Speaks a full spatial overview at startup or during room transitions.</li>
        <li><strong>Guidance Mode:</strong> Values silence, speaking short prompts (e.g. 'Continue.') only when commands change or every 12 seconds as reassurance.</li>
        <li><strong>Alert Mode:</strong> Preempts normal speech to announce immediate safety alerts (e.g. 'Stop. Obstacle ahead.').</li>
        <li><strong>Description Mode:</strong> Speaks a detailed room layout on user demand (pressing the 'D' key).</li>
    </ul>

    <!-- CHAPTER 10 -->
    <h1>Chapter 10: Conversation Memory</h1>
    <h2>10.1 Reducing Cognitive Load</h2>
    <p>Continuous speech commands quickly fatigue the user. The ConversationMemory class stores state variables to suppress duplicate prompts.</p>
    <h2>10.2 Suppression Rules</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>Identical speech sentences are suppressed.</li>
        <li>If the situation and navigation command remain unchanged, the system is silent.</li>
        <li>If nothing changes for 12.0 seconds, a brief reassurance is allowed.</li>
        <li>Safety alerts bypass suppression but are limited to an 8.0-second cooldown for identical repeats.</li>
    </ul>

    <!-- CHAPTER 11 -->
    <h1>Chapter 11: Navigation Logic</h1>
    <h2>11.1 Safe Path Centroid & Steering Decisions</h2>
    <p>The navigation engine processes the fused scene data to determine the safest direction of travel. `PathGeometryAnalyzer` calculates the walkable centroid (center_x). If the path center shifts left or right, the system recommends steering adjustments:</p>
    <pre>
           Walkable Center (center_x)
                   │
    ┌──────────────┼──────────────┐
    ▼              ▼              ▼
Left Shift     Centered       Right Shift
(< 135px)    (135px-185px)     (> 185px)
    │              │              │
    ▼              ▼              ▼
[Command: LEFT] [Command: FORWARD] [Command: RIGHT]
    </pre>

    <!-- CHAPTER 12 -->
    <h1>Chapter 12: Qwen Reasoning</h1>
    <h2>12.1 Local Large Language Model</h2>
    <p>A local Qwen 2.5-VL model (running via Ollama) translates steering commands and safety states into natural, conversational speech. The reasoning engine runs in a background thread to prevent network queries from blocking the main loop.</p>
    <h2>12.2 Fallback Guidance</h2>
    <p>If the local Ollama server is unreachable, the system automatically falls back to deterministic guidance rules. This ensures that steering commands are still generated even during model failures.</p>

    <!-- CHAPTER 13 -->
    <h1>Chapter 13: Kokoro Speech</h1>
    <h2>13.1 Preemptive Audio Queue</h2>
    <p>The speech worker uses a priority-based queue to coordinate synthesized audio playback:</p>
    <table>
        <thead>
            <tr>
                <th>Priority</th>
                <th>Type</th>
                <th>Content Example</th>
                <th>Preemption Rule</th>
            </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
            <tr>
                <td><strong>Priority 0</strong></td>
                <td>Critical Safety Alerts</td>
                <td>"Please stop. Obstacle ahead."</td>
                <td>Interrupts active speech immediately. Flushes lower priority items.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td><strong>Priority 1</strong></td>
                <td>Steering / Guidance</td>
                <td>"Let's move slightly left."</td>
                <td>Queued and played sequentially.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td><strong>Priority 2</strong></td>
                <td>Descriptions / Reassurance</td>
                <td>"The path remains clear."</td>
                <td>Played only when higher priority tasks are complete. Can be interrupted.</td>
            </tr>
        </tbody>
    </table>
    <h2>13.2 Audio Preemption</h2>
    <p>If a Priority 0 warning arrives, the speech worker calls `sounddevice.stop()` to halt active guidance audio immediately, flushes lower priority items, and speaks the warning instantly, prioritizing user safety.</p>

    <!-- CHAPTER 14 -->
    <h1>Chapter 14: Threading Architecture</h1>
    <h2>14.1 Multi-Threaded Execution</h2>
    <p>To prevent slow operations from blocking the real-time loop, the system delegates blocking I/O and HTTP queries to three background threads:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>CameraReaderThread:</strong> Constantly pulls frames from the hardware webcam.</li>
        <li><strong>QwenReasonerThread:</strong> Executes HTTP queries to the local Ollama LLM server, updating a shared guidance variable.</li>
        <li><strong>TelemetryWorkerThread:</strong> Writes JSON logs, feedback logs, and JPEG/NumPy snapshots sequentially using a task queue.</li>
    </ul>

    <!-- CHAPTER 15 -->
    <h1>Chapter 15: Performance Optimization</h1>
    <h2>15.1 Optimizations Summary</h2>
    <table>
        <thead>
            <tr>
                <th>Optimization</th>
                <th>Mechanism</th>
                <th>Latency Impact</th>
                <th>Memory Footprint</th>
            </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
            <tr>
                <td><strong>TensorRT Engines</strong></td>
                <td>Fuses layer execution, FP16 kernel optimization.</td>
                <td>Reduced latency from 110ms to 20ms.</td>
                <td>Allocates ~400 MB GPU memory.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td><strong>GPU Decoders</strong></td>
                <td>Softmax and argmax run on CUDA tensors.</td>
                <td>Reduced latency by 4.0ms, avoided CPU copy.</td>
                <td>Saves PCIe bus bandwidth by 4x.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td><strong>Asynchronous workers</strong></td>
                <td>LLM and logging operations offloaded to background threads.</td>
                <td>Eliminated main loop blocking.</td>
                <td>Safe background task queue.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td><strong>In-place Normalization</strong></td>
                <td>Pre-allocated NumPy buffers for normalization and resizing.</td>
                <td>Eliminated per-frame memory allocation.</td>
                <td>Constant memory footprint.</td>
            </tr>
        </tbody>
    </table>

    <!-- CHAPTER 16 -->
    <h1>Chapter 16: Learning Pipeline</h1>
    <h2>16.1 Telemetry JSONL Logging</h2>
    <p>Every frame's fused metrics are appended to a JSONL log file asynchronously. This log records safety states, path geometry, and latencies.</p>
    <h2>16.2 Auto-Labeling and snapshot capture</h2>
    <p>If the scene confidence drops below 0.45, or the safety state is uncertain, the auto-labeler flags the frame. The background worker saves a JPEG copy of the frame and a NumPy array of the depth map. This builds an offline dataset to retrain the segmentation and depth models later.</p>

    <!-- CHAPTER 17 -->
    <h1>Chapter 17: Error Handling</h1>
    <h2>17.1 Disk Exception Handling</h2>
    <p>Assistive tools must never crash during runtime. Writing log files, dataset snapshots, or feedback entries involves disk operations that can fail due to disk-full, write-protection, or missing directory errors. We wrapped all I/O calls in try-except (OSError, IOError) blocks to prevent crashes.</p>
    <h2>17.2 Model Fallbacks</h2>
    <p>If the GPU context fails or TensorRT fails to allocate buffers, the system exits gracefully, ensuring threads are stopped and camera feeds are released cleanly.</p>

    <!-- CHAPTER 18 -->
    <h1>Chapter 18: Project Demonstration</h1>
    <h2>18.1 Demonstration Scenario</h2>
    <p>When the user runs the system, the following sequential actions occur:  
    1. **Initialization**: Models are loaded into GPU memory, and the system announces: *"Path Vision active. Loading models."*  
    2. **Startup Scan**: The system scans the room silently for 2.5 seconds to build a stable spatial map.  
    3. **Initial Guidance**: The system announces the startup orientation: *"System ready. The corridor ahead is open."*  
    4. **Active Navigation**: The user starts walking. The system remains silent unless an obstacle is detected or the direction changes.</p>

    <!-- CHAPTER 19 -->
    <h1>Chapter 19: Benchmark Results</h1>
    <h2>19.1 Profiling Metrics on RTX 2050</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>Startup Loading Time: 2.427 seconds.</li>
        <li>Shutdown Thread Join: 0.005 seconds.</li>
        <li>CPU RAM Footprint: 795.93 MB.</li>
        <li>Calculated Pipeline Frame Rate: 42.3 FPS.</li>
    </ul>

    <!-- CHAPTER 20 -->
    <h1>Chapter 20: Future Scope</h1>
    <h2>20.1 YOLOv8 Object Detection</h2>
    <p>In Version 2.0, a third TensorRT engine (YOLOv8-nano) can be added in parallel to identify specific objects (e.g. chairs, tables, doors). The detected objects will be formatted as semantic tags and passed to Qwen's prompt builder.</p>
    <h2>20.2 Local Model Embedding</h2>
    <p>To guarantee 100% offline TTS startup, voice weights will be packaged directly within the repository. This removes the need for internet access during the initial launch, ensuring reliability in offline settings.</p>

    <!-- CHAPTER 21 -->
    <h1>Chapter 21: Conclusion</h1>
    <h2>21.1 Project Summary</h2>
    <p>PathVision Final Version 1.0 delivers a local-first, low-latency navigation assistant that achieves 42.3 FPS on laptop hardware. By prioritizing silence over robotic repetition and using priority speech queues, the assistant functions as an intelligent navigation companion. The system meets all performance and reliability targets, providing a robust solution for visually impaired mobility.</p>

